name: Send My Love (To Your New Lover)
Rock Island Line
comments: Recorded by John Lomax and Huddie Ledbetter (Lead Belly) at the Cummins State Farm prison, Gould, Arkansas (spelt "Cumins" on the original release, now known as the Cummins Unit). On this recording, Kelly Pace (sometimes spelt "Kelley") was accompanied by Charlie Porter, L.T. Edwards, WIllie Hubbard, Luther Williams, Napoleon Cooper, Albert Pate and Willie Lee Jones. This was the second recording of "Rock Island Line" made by Lomax and Lead Belly: the first, made a few days earlier on September 29, 1934, at the Tucker Farm prison, near Little Rock, Arkansas (now known as the Tucker Unit) appears to be unissued (as far as we are aware). Lomax and Lead Belly apparently failed to note the names of the performers on this recording.

Rock Island Line
comments: The Rock Island Line (in full, the Chicago, Rock Island and Pacific Railroad) encouraged its employees to take part in extra-curricular activities such as singing in choirs and writing songs to build brand awareness and loyalty (or “boost” in contemporary terminology) amongst their communities. The song Rock Island Line was written by Clarence Wilson, an engine wiper (cleaner) who worked at the Biddle Street Shops, the railroad’s central freight yard and workshop near Little Rock, Arkansas. He was a member of a vocal group, the Rock Island Colored Booster Quartet, that was based at the Biddle Street Shops and this group first performed his song in December 1929.
